notes.text: Forgot to take 1-a-day pill. Not good.

Got ‚Äúnotes‚Äù section working (roughly) in my app. It supports adding photos. When I took this one I was on the bed trying to fart. I spent an hour on that and then in the toilet trying the usual techniques to get things moving. By the time I emerged I had achieved little and felt more even Steptoe than before.

I blame missing the pill yesterday.

Then I came upstairs and moved over all my diary entries from Diaro, which I can now delete.

Things I want to add to the app: 

- geotagging
- hashtags support
- a scrollable note list with image thumbnails 

#ideas

Currently in bed feeling extremely tired after staying up till 3am after watching the stream of Paul McCartney at Glastonbury. Have to go to work thing to seem like someone who joins in.

Trying to think how to write down my mood and its causes just now has forced me to question those causes and feel a bit dismissive of them (in a good way, I think.)

Basically I am very tired and hungry, and that‚Äôs bound to make me gloomy. On top of which, it‚Äôs Sunday.

Picture was seconds before a brief gust of wind almost lifted it into the air and they decided to take it down.

The next challenge was figuring out when to leave. I‚Äôd got there at 12:20. After the food it was the big ‚ÄúCrystal maze‚Äù activity, at about 14:30, which was my cover to run away. Sitting outside making small talk with a group of people for two hours is a long time for me.

I finally bought an ice cream from the Tonibell van by the Thames (toblerone, not great).

When I got home I was extremely tired and T suggested I have a nap, which I did until about 7.

Watched (with one eye) Raducanu‚Äôs first match, straight sets win, good omen. Remember I hate sport and yet watch Wimbledon.

Work pretty smooth and easy, and yet just enough trickiness to make me feel important.

Doorbell rang during meeting and I went to answer. Teams decided to un-blur the pile of dirty washing behind my chair. Adam drew eyes and a mouth on it so it looked like a black cat hiding under a towel. This is now my profile picture.

Anxiety this morning about ageism in employment, as I‚Äôm nearly 50. Picked up by reading about Tony Blackburn‚Äôs show being moved from Friday to Sunday, which he blames on ageism. I should just never look at Twitter.

Woke up a little early and got two washes on and started bread maker (Waitrose malted, really nice). Ate for lunch with whole can of tuna mayo.

Evening walk was good, T very funny. ‚ÄúYellow is the highest viz‚Äù (on seeing an orange hi-viz jacket).

This evening we went through all our old pots of paint to see what condition they were in. We discovered that Farrow and Ball modern emulsion separated into a near solid rubbery layer with a watering layer on top, so it was all useless, including a whole unopened big tin. To my horror they now cost ¬£50-70 a tin! I think they were ¬£30 last time, but that was a decade ago I suppose. I raised the idea with T that we are just decorating to move out. But she was firm with me! 

We also ordered rollers and brushes.

We had ordered paint, brushes and rollers to arrive today, so I waited in for the delivery, but the paint didn‚Äôt come (the rest did). 

I made white bread with an egg in it (and 10g of sugar) thinking this might be like brioche. But it‚Äôs more like yellow bread. I think brioche has butter as well. It looks like Madeira cake.

I watched the last couple of Stranger Thingses, seemed pretty typical and in engaging, a let down after the first tranche of episodes being unusually good.

Really I was more focused on deleting old tweets. Anything that seems like a pointless interjection, or arguing about politics, Brexit, covid, trump, etc. I hope I can cut it back to almost nothing. The problem is I wasted so much time over the years posting such rubbish that after working on it half the day I got back to late 2020. Have signed up to Twitter API so I can script something faster!

Cleaned the bathroom sink and took a stop motion video of the bleach working its magic.

Caught up on some Wimbledon, watched crap on Amazon prime, did Speedy crossword with T, v. successfully.

We walked before dinner and it was lovely at first, but on the way back T talked about hormones and their effects and said something about wishing men had to experience it, and I asked some clarifying question or other - I‚Äôm certain this exact conversation has happened before and the exact same result: furious with me for trying to understand. I was supposed to just listen and nod, not understand. Upset me hugely but I swallowed it.

Selenium most of the day at work, and tiring news about upcoming interviews that I‚Äôll be doing most of. Ended the day with a headache, also due to lack of sleep.

Evening walk much better than yesterday, baby swans amazing. Also nice encounter with black cat.

Arse being ridiculous tonight though.

Interview with Ryan. He had 6 years experience but came across very green and wobbly in the coding challenge. Required tons of help.

Lovely walk but very short (‚Äúnot quick‚Äù as T insisted). By the time we got back Michael Gove had somehow contrived to be sacked, on the day about 40 people resigned.

T convinced acesulfame k is causing my appalling wind.

Paint came. I cut out Ribena to see if there‚Äôs any link to the wind. Also I felt kind of rough in the throat but annoyingly there are several possible explanations: hay fever, was in office Wednesday (lots of Covid about, or could just be a cold), or because I drank neat rum Wednesday evening.

T having angst about parents and how involved in their lives she isn‚Äôt, a feeling I know well.

Belatedly realised that to paint a small bathroom you need to not shower in it for a day or two. Right now there‚Äôs a heat wave. So we seem to be stuck on that part of the plan.

I actually did some work (coding) in the morning, trying to catch up on a frustrating week.

Most of the day was fine mood-wise but nasty bit very late, where T asked me to take the towel wash out and I reached for the wrong basket (having distracted myself with thoughts of Covid) and she switched to contempt for me.

Re: covid I was thinking that the easiest way to estimate unnecessary deaths would be to note that prior to vaccines taking effect, Australia suppressed transmission so effectively (eg. airport quarantine) that they could track and isolate every case, and only had 1000 deaths total. In the same period we had 120,000. So 100k unnecessary deaths would be a minimum estimate.

Last night T said I should exercise early this morning if I wanted. But this morning I lay in bed feeling rubbish, eventually looked at weather forecast and it said 18 degrees at 10am which was about the time. So I went out and walked down the Thames and back up the Kennet in to town and home. On the last bit of Thames where it is tree covered and shady I ran for about 3 minutes (ish) and was comfortable, actually only stopped on the footbridge because of people with bikes. But glad I did stop because in the sun it was blisteringly hot, like opening an oven door. Got home to see T looking sadly at me.

She was having a rough crossing on the crimson tide. We remained in pretty good spirits all day though. Men‚Äôs Wimbledon final not a classic, can‚Äôt decide which competitor I dislike more, exactly like the ongoing Tory leadership fiasco.

Played guitar slightly. Black ric, sounded nice.

Started with a walk but it was short and brisk, due to lack of time, caused by toilet visit, so setting me up with a feeling of resentment instead of healthiness.

Vaguely stressed day; the job interviews we‚Äôre doing have created a vague constant background uneasiness. Also a pile-up of unknowns. Problems that could be huge and complicated. Sometimes this is fun and inviting; sometimes not.

I also wasted a chunk of the day writing comments on the Mail online, an activity that on my deathbed I will want to throttle myself for devoting so many hours to, so pointlessly. Someone is wrong on the Internet: I want them to know, even though they are unreachably stupid or a professional Russian troll. I should just never look at it.

The weekly burger should stop; it is a monstrosity by the time I‚Äôve fried the onions, cheese and burger and added mayo. I don‚Äôt even enjoy it that much. So why eat such a heart attack?
Ben and Jerry Cookie Vermont-ster - We had this new (to us) ice cream tonight. It was a tempting mixture and I will probably finish it, but also it was quite sponge-like and gummy, and odd tasting.

Explosive guts this morning, could be the ice cream.

I worked too late and T was annoyed because she had a plan to pick up prescription by 7:30. So I dashed out to pick it up myself before we ate, problem solved. Sadly that branch of Boots (in the station) is closing.

Then gruelling debate watching, all excruciatingly terrible, rank amateurs on top of being ideologically opposed to wealth redistribution.

Much farting. I had another load of the ice cream.

Excitement mounts for Hottest Day Ever. I set an alarm for every day at 19:30 to play guitar, so I get back into the habit, because I‚Äôm depressed at losing my callouses which means when I want to record some riff I can‚Äôt play it for very long.

Today was the first of the two super hot days. It didn‚Äôt quite deliver the record breaking temperature as advertised. We almost sauntered through it thanks to two air conditioners, but T spent too long in the hellish kitchen and had a continuous headache.

I went outside at about 4pm just to see what it felt like and lasted about 30 seconds - genuinely horrible.

I obeyed my guitar alarm and practised. Just playing made me come up with nice little riffs and things.

Last thing, racked with self-loathing as I think about what I was like as a teenager. Depression creeps up on me. I judge myself a worthless piece of shit and then I can‚Äôt shake the idea. The conclusion is too convincing.

Work was a bizarre lot of things going wrong, we can‚Äôt deploy. Also another terrible meeting with David and his group of high performers, begging us to watch a tedious video made by a former athlete turned motivational speaker (this seems to be the main career open to former athletes). Craig mentioned how we do retros and I whizzed up a quick example and worked it as Craig talked. It felt strangely like we‚Äôd prepared it but it was entirely improvised. Basically want the rest of the business to learn such tools. It is painfully clear that the reason they think we can‚Äôt work from home is because they are useless at it and assume we must be too, can‚Äôt imagine there‚Äôs a better way and lack the humility to ask, but will fall for the meandering bullshit of an athlete making sports-based analogies.

I slept poorly last night and so am exhausted. But we went for walk up to look for signets (no sign), and also before that T made me laugh hysterically by asking ‚Äúhow do you practice for being in an orchestra?‚Äù and it got funnier the more I tried to figure out why I was laughing.

Post heatwave I can at last start on painting bathroom. First thing, a walk. I went some way down the Thames but stopped at the park run area because of the lack of shade. On my way back a couple with an apparently huge age gap (young-ish Japanese woman with 55-ish white haired English guy) stopped me to take their photo by the river. She was very much directing things, he seemed sheepish and apologetic. In town I saw sideways man, also a new Wendy‚Äôs has opened. So now we have that, Taco Bell, Five Guys, at one point we even had Chick Fil A but it‚Äôs gone now. Looking forward to getting an IHOP.

Did the white paint on the ceiling, blue walls tomorrow which will involve more cutting in, but less neck craning.

Feels very good to be making some kind of progress.

No morning walk, instead started painting walls about 10am. Much more fiddly strenuous work. Stopped at 1:10, we had lunch, rested, comically brief walk (got to the Thames, looked at it for 10 seconds, headed back) because a Tesco order was due. Brought it in, then did the cutting in for the second coat, put rice on, went back to do the rolling, and all done.

T depressed by call with David.
Boiler man cometh. He found nothing wrong with it. But it continues to often stop producing hot water at the worst possible time: when you‚Äôre in the shower.

Last week I fixed a slow query that was inconveniencing Primark and it was finally released yesterday. It worked perfectly. There was something confusing about it, but i exactly figured it out and pinpointed the exact cause. It felt great. I also made solid progress in another area, and got drawn into Jamie‚Äôs team to help break some analysis paralysis. I generally felt really good at my job, much as I sometimes feel mediocre. It‚Äôs two imposters.

Also we had a great long walk this evening. My back is still bad from recent DIY efforts but I‚Äôm keeping chipper regardless.

Then as I brushed my teeth I thought of funny names for dolphins, and the best was Mark.

Replaced bathroom fan again. 2nd time in about 7 months. It was notable that the actual fan rotor was stiff, wouldn‚Äôt spin by hand, whereas the new replacement spins freely. It‚Äôs probably choked up with dust.

Earlier mood was pretty mixed. Fell out with T because she hated technology and thought that would be a problem for me. We made up pretty soon and I joked that as we hugged all the kitchen appliances were applauding.

Started day with my walk, which went on a bit long, then in evening I baked cookies (Menier mix) and we did a walk in the dark and stopped at the proper Thames path because some intimidating young people were on a bench.

When we got back I ate 5 cookies which was 48g of sugar.

Ages ago I put a new cold tap on the bath, having ordered a complete new mixer thing of the right type and just cannibalising the parts needed. Today T suggested doing the same for the hot, to see if it would fix the problem of the last few months (same reason boiler man was summoned on the 1st of this month). It didn‚Äôt help. But it was a puzzle at first as to how to switch off the water supply, eventually remembering that it‚Äôs easy thanks to the water softener plumbing which has a bypass setup.

We had two grocery deliveries, first from Tesco involved a minor disaster where I tried to pick up a large apple pie and it slid out of the pathetic packaging. We threw most of it away but in fact it‚Äôs likely we would have done so anyway. We later ate the remaining third with cream. Then a Waitrose delivery which was uneventful

Heat unbearable now. It hasn‚Äôt fallen below 29 since last Sunday.

Seems strange to be noting this because work has generally felt great at Fiscal, as small scale and amateurish as the surrounding set-up has turned out to be. But I spent today mostly recapping what I‚Äôd been doing, for a succession of wider audiences, to great feedback, and felt generally talented and so on. I‚Äôve been beating myself up for years in a pattern that is apparently quite standard: the child who stands out as smart in their infancy is only being compared to 30 other kids, and thus may be too impressed at themselves for being good at reading (say). Then throughout my entire career I‚Äôve been significantly more talented at software than anyone else I‚Äôve worked with. But this is just because of the fairly limited circles I‚Äôve moved in. I‚Äôve compared myself to great exponents from afar, in a way that doesn‚Äôt dent one‚Äôs ego so much. But over the last decade I‚Äôve developed a loud inner voice of self criticism that likes to remind me that I‚Äôm probably nothing special and the world is full of people who are better at what I do than I am. But this is utterly irrational, not because it‚Äôs not true but because it literally makes no difference to anything. I can forget about it, and take pleasure in being what I am, and I‚Äôm hugely fortunate in that.

Around 11th Aug I started counting calories to keep within 1800 per day, having become very casual about cramming my mouth with biscuits, chocolate, ice cream at all hours of the day. Even a cup of drinking chocolate is 240 calories.

I wrote an app to track it all and produce stats and now I‚Äôm a nerd about it, which seems to be really helping me to stick to it. It‚Äôs about a month later, still haven‚Äôt weighed myself though.

Having been thinking of low-level crimes that deserve a light sentence. Best one so far is ‚Äúcontempt of court, but not all of it.‚Äù

Oh and the Queen died.

Tremendously spooky fog for morning walk, dead trees looking like something from medieval-style fantasy movie.

T hugely pissed off with me last thing, can‚Äôt remember why but went to bed without resolution.

First thing T still seemingly angry. I tried to ignore for a while. Then thought about wasting my life feeling bad and made up with her. Then spent ages being affectionate, really making an effort to let her know how I feel. It sounds strange but I think for months now I have been bottling up such feelings on the assumption that she will find them annoying. But just releasing them and being honest and open is impossible to stop once I start. And she doesn‚Äôt seem annoyed yet.

Dead trees back to normal on very nice afternoon walk.
Finished cursed jigsaw. Four pieces missing?!
Beautiful autumn.
Festival dismantlement. Geese still absent.
Started logging my calories in a spreadsheet, trying to stick to 1800 a day.

Happier than I‚Äôve been in a long time, mostly from regularly making sure I tell/show T that I love her.

At the weekend I got her a C64 mini, a little plastic emulator box. This evening I upgraded the firmware so it could read a USB stick with disk images on it, and then got Flimbo‚Äôs Quest to run (with some arsing about).

Work feels okay too. In fact it feels like I‚Äôm very good at it but also that it isn‚Äôt that important (this is not true; the economy is a shitshow and I would definitely prefer not to be looking for work).

Need to keep this mental balance somehow. If I can avoid hurting my back, keep controlling my calories, exercise, show my feelings‚Ä¶
Meltdown!
Set up swytch on my Brompton today.

First day of a week off. Last Wednesday I was given a bottle of rum as a token of appreciation. I‚Äôm only halfway through some cognac so won‚Äôt open it for weeks.

Just cut T‚Äôs hair.

Noticed vision problems today.

It happened twice and both times it was after sitting on the toilet for ages (bad tummy).

I would then try to look at text on a screen and it would be fuzzy and indistinct.

A feeling that there was something getting in the way of text I was looking at. Like a floater or smudge, distorting the text. Also a bit like an after burn from looking at a bright light.
Picked up new glasses today (varifocals). These are the first of hopefully two pairs from specsavers.

Birthday experiment: as usual, chocolate ganache cake to be eaten over four days between the two of us. But to really confuse my body, going to have an absolute blow out. Hence melted chocolate croissants for breakfast.

Went back to specsavers to choose different frames. We browsed for a while and I tried them on. It was late opening day but we had about 30 mins to actually make the choice because they made us wait for ages. So I had to pick two frames. On the way home I had a tiny sense of T being taken aback by how I‚Äôd put my foot down, but we got home and ate; all fine. But something happened during the evening and she was very withdrawn and unhappy. I began to react and got hit by insecurity, self-loathing, my usual end-of-the-world crisis thinking. She eventually told me it was because she‚Äôd picked out frames on the website and I hadn‚Äôt gone with her choices, in particular a pair with slightly loud (IMO) hinge decorations. She felt like she wasted her time and effort on something that wasn‚Äôt appreciated. It would probably sound trivial if described like this to anyone else (which will never happen) but it felt like the end of the world. Although in the end I have to choose the glasses that I will be wearing, I still love the activity of discussing and choosing together, just because it is us doing something, which is my reason for living. Also she has to look at me in the glasses, so I should have thought about that.
So, now just over a week since the start of Birthday Experiment. I weighed myself - lightest I‚Äôve been since May 2017
Today is start of first ‚Äúeat whatever I want‚Äù weekend. As if by magic some naughty treats arrived.
Lunch looks weird today because I forgot to have any.
Started coming down with cold. (Covid LFT negative)

Still coughing.

Last Ken Bruce R2 show!

Waist 86.5 but seems to crash this site when I add it!

Today I did a smashin' showcase that was really show-offy, I booked an engineer to fix the washer-dryer (next Thursday), I booked off the week before the coronation.
Rehosted this app on my own storage account, will see what happens to costs

We each showered, using the tiny towels. I forgot to open the window, or put the shower curtain inside the bath, so by the end it was a sauna. Inexplicably there's a bath mat draped over the side of the bath so I made that soaking wet. I did get clean though. The towel was just about adequate, though I think the opened window did most of the work.

I watched Asoka, dreadful dialogue. Then down to see Roland off, him dishing out orders left and right, and in fact he continued texting pointless suggestions to Tanya from his taxi.

I washed the tiny towels in the bedroom sink with the Dr Beckmann goo and hot water from the kettle. This was semi-arduous, not something I can see myself doing daily (although this possibility was later ruled out).

Then lunch (bread and pastrami we got yesterday, and some of Tanya's cucumber.) As we ate David serenaded us with a continuous monologue about energy providers, public transport, water and sewage provision.

Then two trips into town. The first was a gentle walk with Sue. We visited Wilko, currently in closing-down mode and without much stock remaining. Sue and Tanya bought some cushions. There was a record playing over the tannoy that had a melody in mixolydian mode and I found it intriguing, but no idea who it was. I kept checking my phone to see if the Amazon locker was ready for me, but it wasn't. We rested for a while on a bench in a little corner area with tall trees over it like a canopy, and then headed back home.

The moment we got home, I got a text telling me the locker was ready, so that was the next very short trip, just me. I got the stuff as quickly as I could. On the return journey there were three teenaged girls just ahead of me who stopped to have a dance when they reached a coffee shop that was playing Chic's Good Times, as if they got trapped in a force field - this is how young people stay entertained in small town centres.

On arriving home I went straight into trying out the wifi dongle on Sue's laptop, but it seemed to be a dud. Tried it in Tanya's laptop and that didn't light up either. So I wrapped it up for return (also via locker).

Tanya and I cooked the bacon joint, mashed potato and mixed vegetables. It was pretty much a triumph. Tanya had been plagued all day by nagging texts from Roland and was very pleased to be able to tell him how smoothly dinner had gone (and that she'd taken Sue to town.) Also he is now panicking because his washing machine's rubber seal is also mouldy.

After the main course David and I had small glasses of the wine. I looked at their wine glasses (which Sue and David encouraged me to use) but they all had a very thick layer of ingrained dust and grime, some literally draped with cobwebs in the top of the cupboard, so just used a couple of small glasses that looked as if they might see regular use.

This little foray into middle class sophistication coincided with David finding a bit of classical music he wanted to listen to via Radio 3 on the TV. He closed his eyes and hummed vaguely along. This is how we found him when we came in with the wine and coffee cake, Sue warning us "There's ten more minutes of this." She was openly contemptuous, making a point of asking "Is it over?" at the end.

Then we sat watching TV for ages. At bedtime I apologised to Tanya for being snippy while making the dinner. Throughout the afternoon I kept checking the towels to see if they were dry. They weren't! This is why mangles had to be invented.

Up without washing again.

Tanya stressed attempting to get up early due to Roland's insistence on going to some pointless cafe with her and Sue, and then it didn't happen anyway because he'd changed tack and was hectoring them about the state of the freezer. I helped (?) by hacking all the ice out of the back, but the innards are still full of ice and it is probably just irretrievably broken.

I also investigated Sue's laptop and its inability to detect its own wifi support. Plugged it into the router to get internet, checked for drivers (it's out of support so it had no updates). Also noticed that the battery is dead.

Turned out David's identical laptop is in the same state except his wifi is fine. So I ordered a wifi dongle and two replacement batteries. The dongle to Amazon locker tomorrow, the batteries to the house (at some point next week.)

Subway for lunch (meatballs: mistake).

Tanya and I out to pick up Amazon locker stuff and also food shop. Sainsbury's for cleaning stuff (no HG spray so I ordered it to come to the house). Got Flash bleach anyway, despite the household's terror of bleach.

We also bought two very small towels, out of desperation more than anything.

We found two sets of evening meals in M&S (a bacon joint, two beef things, two kinds of vegetables and potatoes) and some sandwich meat (chicken, pastrami, ham), fretting about whether it would fit. Forgot olive spread, sadly. But I got a bottle of the Beaujolais I like.

Then home to cram it in the fridge. It fitted. Then Roland had a new plan - to take us down to the garage at the bottom of the garden to look at Damien's books and CDs. Seemed distasteful picking over it, though fortunately there was no moral dilemma because we didn't want any of it: all covered in cigarette ash, CDs were 90% things I have, 10% I don't want. The odd book about maths or science that was interesting but as Tanya said, we'd be better off buying a new copy. She got me to photograph a few sets of books as a memento.

KFC for dinner, ordering was a farce. David pretending not to know what a "side" was in the context of fast food. Then they sent the wrong things (on the bone instead of boneless).

Within minutes of us finishing, Bruno showed up with daughter Tara, who we last saw as kid and is now a teenager, very obviously bored and cringing at everything, understandably. I did her a slight favour by looking at my phone at one point, which seemingly gave her permission to do likewise. Bruno held court (as a jester) and was alarmingly incapable of relaxing. I find him psychotic. His way with Sue has a kind of aggression to it, difficult to describe, but she is obviously terrified of him and (to my surprise) openly dropped hints such as "Isn't it about time you were off?" He responded by hugging her like a mafia boss.

I found a pile of Private Eye issues outside the bedroom, top of the pile was from 1963.

I did a tiny bit more work this morning and also informed others of the outcome of the police meeting, making them all aware that it's a murder/manslaughter investigation, and that I am trapped here until end of next week at least with patchy ability to work.

Tanya and I down to the cellar to inspect the washing machine. The rubber seal is indeed pretty badly affected by black mould spots and smears. We don't want to use it, so how can we wash towels? How can we wash ourselves?

To the animal care centre (where they got Winston) for lunch at their cafe. I had a full English breakfast and a huge slice of coffee and walnut cake (and mug of tea). Quick browse of their charity shop (DVDs for 20p).

I ordered a few things from Amazon, including rubber gloves, nesquik cartons, travel kettle, Dr Beckmann's handwash laundry detergent, an eye mask.

In the afternoon I worked in the lounge, Sue insisting on muting the TV no matter how much I assured her it didn't bother me.

Pizza for dinner. David insists on anchovies, he has jars and tins of them especially for adding to pizza. I ate an entire 12" pepperoni one. Tanya ate half of a chicken one (she said it was mostly cheese.) The other Jacksons said it was the best pizza place but I think the cheese was mostly mild cheddar.

Reused the towel for shower, quite manky.

Police came round to update the family. It was obviously a personalised PR exercise, repeating the mantra that they're following an established process and "it takes time", which is why they couldn't tell us anything solid after four weeks.

Extraordinary moment when the DI boasted of his involvement with the Nicola Bulley case, in which the police released private information about the deceased in a doomed attempt to make the public lose interest, and then her body washed up down river and the media moved on.

Interesting to hear him say that the ability of forensic experts to divine the time of death from a body is pure fiction.

Sue and David (understandably) at pains to appear good parents of a difficult (50 year old) child. They described a similar situation in March where Sue found him with a pillow around his head, and bruises on both sides of his torso, and a black eye, claiming he tripped over his TV, obviously untrue and it must have been a related attack. The DI found this significant, as Damien was found dead with a pillow around his head last month. Family dumfounded after the meeting that this had suddenly been noted as significant after weeks. But then, it's highly likely Sue forgot to say half of this until now, or that she has conflated details from the two occasions.

But main disaster is that although he said that they might interview Tanya tomorrow (the sooner the better), later she got a message that it wouldn't be until next Tuesday. Then it might take two days until she can sign the statement. So we're prisoners here for another week at least.

Roland made us go out to feed the ducks. Lovely landscape. I mostly fed a large and noisy gull.

Not getting on with main bedroom light. Need an eye mask.

Showered with a towel we found in the room. After I hung it on the stair rail with the idea of reusing it in a couple of days. The show works well enough for me.

The kettle in the kitchen has a broken lid mechanism. The freezer has a mysterious bin in front of it, like a warning sign: "do not enter". We later have a look at Roland's encouragement and it has a horrible fishy smell. There's a red warning triangle that means it isn't working.

The hot taps produce cold water (I'm told this is a deliberate policy decision).

Most of day pottering about awkwardly, I did some work though.

David is prone to long, apparently impromptu (but probably well rehearsed) speeches on political topics. Sue is like a frightened bird. Roland is insufferably bossy. Sue and David are hopelessly indecisive and prone to live with things any self-respecting person (with sufficient money, which they have) would sort out. They could do it, but they don't. This gives Roland a problem to solve, and he revels in it, being the kind of person who is unable to cease issuing instructions to whoever is in earshot.

No shower today.

Got some work done, in fact mostly in the bedroom with 2nd laptop serving as a TV. Meanwhile poor Tanya out with Sue and Roland at a cafe.

Travelling to Lancaster on the train.

Panicky morning of last minute packing, though most of it done last night. Also I watered all the plants.

Very worried that we will be burgled. Haven't been away this long with the house unoccupied. However I think the statistics show that your chance of being burgled is unrelated to whether you are at home.

The morning spent fretting over what to do with Sue and David. Get them out of the house? David is not keen, and has an excuse to rebuff any suggestions (Williamson's park was Tanya's idea today).

In the end Tanya went out with Sue to buy newspapers and wander around, and I shopped at Sainsbury's and M&S. Made a poor choice of trolley, some sort of unwieldy wide/short thing.

Then home in time to make dinner, another triumph (brisket, roast veg, bubble and squeak), although in truth we burned the vegetables, especially the onions, which were ruined. A bit more wine (David and me).

Perfectly timed so we were cleared away for the arrival of Bruno, on his own this time and far more muted in mood.

At some point Roland phoned, and it was a joy to have him on the other end of the speakerphone experience, where Sue holds the wrong end of the phone to her face and addresses him, while David burbles away to Tanya and me, unable to stop himself, with the result that Roland can't hear anything clearly.

Bizarre creepy remarks from David about (professor) Alice Roberts. He said he was torn between attraction and irritation, accusing her of excessive self-promotion.

Got up early and moved work laptop into the little room at the back where Roland had been staying before he went home, with the idea of doing morning meeting. But the wifi turned out to be terrible in that room so I had to switch hurriedly to the (famous) middle room on the ground floor. New manager Paul joined the call and was a bit nervous.

I had some work I'd done over the last couple of days in little bursts, and was able to "release" in two PRs during the day to make it seem like I was working steadily. Also another one that was much simpler.

But main incident of the day was that Tanya got a call from the police (Helen?) saying they would come round immediately to speak to her. I waited in the lounge with her until they arrived. Sue said the most incredible unhelpful and weird things, then suggested we insist that I be present, which the police already ruled out, and then she lurked outside the room and later in the kitchen. I went upstairs and comfort ate (brioche, cookies, chocolate milk) and watched Marvel, extremely worried, unable to work.

When Tanya emerged it was far more gentle and less traumatic than she had feared, a huge relief. She spent the afternoon trying to help them buy a new landline phone, to no avail, as it is almost possible to discuss anything with both of them without trigger an outburst of bickering and years of pent up hostility come pouring out.

In the evening, fish pie, and interminable TV watching. Every night the routine is that when it gets dark, Sue asks David to draw the curtains, and he delays and whines, objecting to being asked, eventually giving in. There's no humour to any of it, just rancid bitterness.

Tanya out with S&D for middle of the day, so home alone. Pretty productive at work, then popped into town to get milk, dinner and sanitary products (had to visit multiple shops to get the right kind). But I also stopped for a Big Mac and fries, which I ate sat on the low window ledge at the front of the McDonalds, surrounded by stressed out mums. Town very crowded - I guess still school summer holiday period.

A few minutes after I got back Bruno let himself in, and said something about bringing a painting round from Damien's. He said something quite weird about how strange it was that he was "murdered 10 doors down and his flat was full of paintings by someone 6 doors down". I had no idea what the irony was, or whether I'd misunderstood, but just nodded politely.

The dinner I bought earlier was lasagne, and we cooked it to get out of having to bicker about a takeaway, seemed well received.

Then Tanya noticed a fresh horror which is that the pipe under our bedroom sync has a slow drip. Weirdly there's a bit of kitchen roll on a shelf in the sink cupboard, soaking wet and disgusting.

Woke up with a headache, which continued, though was seemingly controlled a bit by ibuprofen.

I pinched an aluminium tray to put under the sink leak, removed the old bit of kitchen roll, and we'll see how it goes.

Did a call with Paul (new manager), he was at pains to appear knowledgeable.

Batteries for S&D laptops arrived, plugged them in and they seemed to work.

Police meeting: one striking new revelation, some prescription morphine was found, intended for a Mark Carthy, a name that meant nothing to the family.

Felt snotty this morning, assumed at first it was dust from moving the old mattress out of the way.

By 15:20 I was starting to feel more like I had a cold so did a covid test. Went to get my phone to start a timer and when I got back to the test it had a really dark red second line. So I have covid at last.

Ordered 25 tests and 60 good masks.

Tanya has quarantined me downstairs (bedroom and office) and brought me fajitas and cookies. She's wearing a mask whenever I see her, and we've opened some windows (reasoning that a bit of pollution for a few days is a reasonable trade off if we can avoid infecting her too.)

It is the 5th day after our journey from Lancaster with the coughing fat man. Quite a long incubation. Could be from Tuesday at the office where there was some daft event involving eating pizza with the usual disregard for hygiene.
Aimless bookend of a day, felt work-stressed, we went shopping for a bunch of last minute stuff, sandwiches for tomorrow, and picked up a sort of power-assisted exercise thing for your feet.

Journey home, went extremely smoothly despite warnings about limited services due to strikes (this is probably why it went smoothly, not as many passengers due to other people heeding the warnings.)

Only pain was a huge man who looked like he was on the verge of death, coughing expressively in our direction for most of the second leg.

Woke up feeling sort of rough but I did get some fitful sleep. But felt worse as the day went in, lots of sneezing and snot, muscle/bone aches. No dry cough yet, not much in the way of headaches.

Had a Five Guys cheeseburger for lunch.

Received new boxes of masks we ordered yesterday.

Did another test, T line is still angry red.

Today hopefully the last day of total isolation, having spent the last few days in bed. 

Tuesday to Friday I worked in bed. Other than that I ate delivered food, watched crap, and felt horribly filthy and unhealthy (an accurate feeling.) The highlight of each day was the covid test, the first 9 of which were very strongly positive. Yesterday was the first noticeable change.

Today's test looked completely negative after 15 minutes. I looked again in stronger daylight and saw a faint grey line, but that was after over 40 minutes.

Went outside for the first time in a long time, walked as briskly as I could. Felt weak and dizzy most of the time.

I feel a self-pitying outrage that my every attempt to restart running is, seemingly necessarily, thwarted by some interruption. I did two 5K runs in August, only for the family tragedy situation to intervene, and then Covid. I am now far worse than back to square one. On the other hand I recognise that this is a pathetic complaint.
A slightly longer run, 5.7km, up toward Mapledurham.
First 5K since September 2020.

Damien's funeral. A long day. We travelled up yesterday afternoon but that feels like a week ago. I got up with my alarm at 7:20 (negotiated with T last night to give her time time prepare for breakfast), showered and dressed, but T became increasingly unhappy with the idea of going down for breakfast at all. I went alone and had only cereal, awkwardly.

The hotel is mostly nice, but with odd little examples of disrepair. The bathroom sink's plug is not attached to the chain. Maybe that's a normal thing, to stop flooding? I know nothing about hotels. But then why leave the chain dangling into the hole? Also various bits of rust in the bath and shower. By the way, the shower has just perfectly the wrong height. Really the galling thing is that this slight shabbiness costs over ¬£300 a night.

Back to sit with T and she hit a severe low, cursing the situation (understandably). Unusually she agreed to me writing a text on her behalf to Roland who was relentlessly texting and phoning demanding what her plans were, in his usual subtle way. I said she was struggling emotionally etc. and couldn't make any decision just now.

We made it to the house and the dreaded Emma was there along with Karen (the present Mrs Bruno). The funeral people were quite late. We shuffled into the back of a limo that would follow the hearse. Hilarity began immediately as Sue and David bickered about everything and nothing, and we played musical chairs to find the best possible arrangement for our backsides. With a coffin in front of us.

A beautiful day, crisp sunshine, Lancaster's lovely sandstone buildings. Bruno to the driver: "Do dead bodies smell after they've been dead a few weeks?"

Inside the priory, it's a good sized Anglican Church set-up. There were several dozen mourners and we processed to the front row and sat down. Scouse priest read out his sermon and it was bafflingly untruthful. What is the point of summing up a person's life by describing someone else's, a fictional person? It was also extremely heavy on the religious stuff, and this is a family of staunch atheists (although Bruno will believe almost anything if he puts his mind to it). David in particular was joining in with the Amen chorus, and he will usually talk (at length) of how much he despises the hypocrisy of it all.

On the other hand it was noticeable that after a few minutes no one was repeating Amen. The religious material was relentless, entire Bible passages were read, Lazarus was raised. There were three hymns, which I tried to sing in my wavering voice. Abide With Me was quite moving though, especially the second verse, almost Taoist in a way. (Found out in the car later that I was the only person who had this reaction, which seemed strangely like material for another verse).

T held up very well as a stream of well-wishers came up to introduce themselves. Then a quite lengthy drive to the graveyard, more religion, and where the siblings threw a handful of earth into the grave, including (at the last minute) T just because David didn't feel able and she is really just here to support him.

Next stop was a little bar with an upstairs room, Gregson Arts and Community Centre, where we sat an and ate tiny cakes and I had a tea. But also mysteriously I developed severe hay fever. Tan and I walked to Boots and back to get Benadryl, though not before I was grilled suspiciously and aggressively by a relative called Liz who works in a pharmacist and was almost offended that she didn't already have something in her car for me.

Anyway, I was fine as soon as I got out of the building, and symptoms returned when I got back. As we were finally leaving for real, it became clear that the culprit was a late-flowering plant in the hallway, which I stood next to for 30 seconds to read leaflets and was violently attacked by sneezing.

The last hour or so at Gregson consisted of T and I sitting with Sue's brother Mike who bored on about Israel and various random historical topics in an indistinct mumble.

Then to 28 Regent Street and an interminable sitting session with S & D bickering. The goal was to eat fish pie and fuck off, but it was torturously drawn out because Emma disappeared upstairs so it was impossible to get a decision on how many to cook for. Reminiscent of how we had to wait about two weeks for a decision on whether we'd need to book a hotel and thus ran out of options.

Eventually we heard they were going out to eat and so T and I got the food in the oven, polished it off (as we were eating, Emma walked out announcing that she and R were going to "get some FOOD", the emphasis implying that this was in contrast to whatever we might be eating) and at long last trudged back to the hotel in the dark.

More soul searching and self-berating from T in the hotel room. We talked until room service became unavailable (9:30), a disaster as we'd skipped lunch entirely. So I got us McDonald's delivered to the lobby. T's first ever thick shake, which she was well into.

The train journey to Lancaster, with the only notable incidents being the necessity to argue primly with someone sat in our reserved seats. The first one was great because the woman insisted vociferously she was in the right seat. When the ticket collector came I asked him conversationally (but slightly loudly) how often there was an unfortunate double-booking incident? "Hardly ever" he said. "Oh how strange," I countered, "because that lady over there and I both have the same seat reserved." And of course when he examined her ticket she wasn't even on the right train. Her attitude changed so suddenly it was hard not to feel a rush of intensely petty triumph. It's this kind of feeble mediated confrontation which must stand in for the primordial antler-butting that our instincts presumably demand of us.

Woke up and resolved to take proper advantage of the breakfast I've already paid for. Plonked myself at a table and a nice lady asked me what I wanted, to which I replied "Pancakes, bacon and maple syrup, and tea." Tea arrived in minutes, the meal soon after, which turned out to be five pancakes and five rashers, with a pot of syrup and icing sugar on the pancakes too. I followed up with Weetabix and I estimated about 1500 calories altogether. It's no wonder Americans are so enormous.

T still very unhappy due to the early starts, the awkward family interaction etc. Mike still staying at Regent St. We got there to find they had a plan to eat out at the Barn in Scorton (near Preston), which meant travelling in two cars. Sue and David divided between the cars so they could both use the front seat. We went with Sue and Roland/Emma. I sat in the middle (as always, this trip). Emma drove - apparently she won't let Roland drive as she believes he's terrible at it. She is aggressive and enjoys annoying other drivers.

When we arrived at the table and looked at the menus, Roland tried to take our orders while Emma screeched at him that he wasn't doing it properly. There was otherwise a fairly warm atmosphere, some humour. The prospect of fancy food goes a long way toward cheering people up. Most orders the club sandwich, but after my huge sugary breakfast I didn't feel up to anything served with chips. I had soup. This turned out to be a good decision because the so-called sandwich looked like enough food for two. Sue and T struggled, Roland and Emma polished theirs off.

Then to get out you had to take a winding path through a gift shop - clever! Except ultimately very annoying because suddenly Sue realised she'd lost her favourite hat. To get back in and look for it involved a second long trip. It didn't turn up.

Then Roland and Emma were keen to visit the Wallings ice cream factory, where I (unwisely) decided to get the "two scoops" cone so I could mix two flavours. But it was more like 20 scoops, a small bucket of icecream, enough to make you violently ill if you tried to eat it all. I had throw most of it away.

Then when we got back, R&E disappeared again, this time apparently to Blackpool. Extraordinary how guilty R has made T feel and then he drops her in it like this. The evening was truly miserable because Sue T and I had KFC, which was a saga in itself - they didn't accept the order for a very long time, so T and I set off to walk to the restaurant and buy it ourselves. But we got the notification that our order was on the way just as we were in sight of the restaurant! So had to race the biker back to the house. Arrived seconds after him.

Before all that there was a fraught discussion between David and Mike about them getting stuff from the chip shop. David hasn't had a steak and kidney pie for seven months (I think he may even have been counting the days) and was overjoyed when Mike said he'd get fish and chips (due to his unshakeable Catholic habit of eating fish on Fridays). But David made the mistake of jokingly saying he would "allow" Mike to have fish and chips if Mike got him a pie. Mike got huffy at this, and a bizarrely immature tiff broke out ending with David sulkily saying "fine, do whatever you want!"

Mike is clearly having an awful time.

Momohouse for dinner.

Went to station to use photo-me booth, to renew passport and get joint railcard.
Ran 6km, first proper run since last August.
Insane confrontation with James Pobgee. He shouted down a teams call at me. Under-ate by a lot. Slept badly.

Went into office especially for meeting with Mike Johns (contracts expert) and James P sat in. Mike contradicted everything James had been shouting at me on Thursday. I am pleased about this, obviously, but still extremely annoyed that I spent the weekend enormously agitated about it. Almost completely relaxed now.

5.5 km run, so with Sunday and today, this is the first time I've done two consecutive runs over 5 km since autumn 2019, nearly 5 years ago. At that time I could run 10km in 56.5 mins. At my current pace it would take me 65 minutes (and I would feel quite bad for a few days.) But I want to get back up to 10km running on a regular basis, at least at weekends. I may also start walking to work at least during the summer. It's only once a week but it's another 8km of exercise.
Watched 'ET' followed by 'Inside Out'.
Listening to 'Brexit - A Love Story?'

Jamie Mulcahy's first day at Fiscal.

Got new Roland V-Drums sound module.

Learned that buses accept contactless payment.

First listened to 'Fortunately' podcast.

Wrote song "I'm a Doctor".

Saw Kristin Hersh at Sub 89. Loudness drove us to a corridor where the vibration was even worse.

Went to Henley branch of HSBC to get mortgage agreement in principle,  came out feeling immensely rich.

Sold a secondhand mattress for ¬£250 on ebay, never would have believed someone would pay so much.

Breakfast includes a digestive biscuit that I had at about 2:30am to counteract a weird nauseous sensation I sometimes get at night. Just as I'm drifting off to sleep I suddenly get a sense of anxiety and dizziness and have to wake up and swallow frantically. Is it a kind of water boarding by mucus? I don't know. It's exhausting and nauseating.
